Robert Hammond is the co-founder and former executive director of Friends of the High Line. He's worked as a consultant for a variety of entrepreneurial endeavors and nonprofits, including the Times Square Alliance, Alliance for the Arts and National Cooperative Bank (NCB).

Hammond is also a self-taught artist. From 2002 to 2005 he served as an Ex-Officio Trustee of the Metropolitan Museum of Art. He was awarded the Rome Prize from the American Academy in Rome in 2009.

aws-transcripts.transcript: The Highline is an old elevated rail line that runs for a mile and 1/2 right through Manhattan, And it was originally a freight line that ran down 10th Avenue, and it became known as Death Avenue because so many people were run over by the trains that the railroad hired a guy on horseback to run in front, and he became known as the West Side Cowboy. But even with the cowboy about one person, ah, month was killed and run over, so they elevated it. They built a 30 feet in the air right through the middle of the city, but with the rise of interstate trucking, it was used less and less, and by 1980 the last train rode. It was a trainload of frozen turkeys, they say, at Thanksgiving from the meat packing district, and then it was abandoned, and I live in the neighborhood, and I first read about it in The New York Times on an article set that said it was gonna be ah, demolished, and I assumed someone was working to preserve it or save it. I could volunteer, but realized no one was doing anything. I went to my first community board meeting, which I had never been to one before and sat next to another guy named Joshua David, who was a travel writer. And at the end of the meeting, we realized we were the only two people that were sort of interested in the project. Most people wanted to tear it down, so we exchanged business cards and we kept calling each other and decided to start this organization, Friends of the High Line and the Goal First was just saving it from demolition. But then we also wanted to figure out what we could do with it. And what first attracted me are interested me. Was this this view from the street, which is this, you know, steel structure of sort of rusty, this industrial relic. But when I went up on top, it was a mile and 1/2 of wildflowers running right through the middle of Manhattan, you know, with views of the Empire State Building and the Statue of Liberty in the Hudson River. And that's really where we started. The idea of coalesced around. Let's make this a park, and let's have it be sort of inspired by this wild scape At the time, there was a lot of opposition. Mayor Giuliani wanted to tear it down. I'm gonna fast forward through a lot of lawsuits and a lot of sort of community engagement. Mayor Bloomberg came in office. He was very supportive, but we still had to make the economic case. You know, this was after 9 11 The city was in tough times, so we commissioned an economic feasibility study to try to make the case, and it turns out we got those numbers wrong. We thought it would cost $100,000,000 to build. So far, it's cost about 150,000,000. And the main case was, this is gonna make good economic sense for the city. So we said over a 20 year time period, the value to the city and increased property values and increased taxes would be about 250,000,000. That was enough. It really got the city behind it. It turns out we were wrong on that. Now people estimate it's created about 1/2 $1,000,000,000 or will create about 1/2 $1,000,000,000 in tax revenues for the city, redid a design competition, selected a design team. We worked with them to really create a design that was inspired by that sort of wild scape. There's three sections. We opened the first section in 2000 and nine. It's been sort of successful beyond our dreams. Last year we had about 2,000,000 people, which is about 10 times what we ever estimated. This is one of my favorite features in Section one. It's this empathy at a right over 10th Avenue, and the first section ends at 20th Street Right now. The other thing it's generated obviously a lot of economic value. It's also inspired, I think, a lot of great architectures. There's a point where you can stand here and see buildings by Frank Gehry, John Nuke Bell, Shaggy Roban, Neil Denarii and the Whitney is moving downtown and is building that their new museum right at the base of the high line and this has been designed by Renzo Piano, and they're gonna break ground in May, and we've already started construction on section two. This is one of my favorite features, this flyover, where you're eight feet off the surface of the high line, running through a canopy of trees. The high line used to be covered in billboards. And so we've sort of taken a playful take where instead of framing advertisement, it's gonna frame people and views of the city. This was just installed last month, and then the last section it was gonna go around the rail yards, which is the largest undeveloped site in Manhattan, and the city has planned for better for worse, a 12,000,000 square feet of development that the Highline is gonna ring around. But you know what? Really, I think makes the Highline special is the people. And honestly, even though I love the designs that we were building, I was always frightened that I wouldn't really love it because I fell in love without wild scape and how could you re create that magic? But what I found is it's in the people and how they use it. That, to me, makes it so special. In just one quick example is I realized right after we opened that there are all these people holding hands on the high line and I realized New Yorkers don't hold hands. Um, we just don't do that in outside, but you see that happen on the high line. And I think that's, you know, the power that that public space can have to transform, how people experience their city, um, and interact with each other. Thanks.
